Note:
LLVM IR Parser - Builds AST from LLVM IR tokens

This file implements parsing for LLVM IR (Intermediate Representation).
Handles module-level declarations, function definitions, basic blocks,
and SSA-form instructions.

LLVM IR AST Node Types:
- LLVM_MODULE - Module container
- LLVM_FUNCTION - Function definition
- LLVM_BASIC_BLOCK - Basic block with label
- LLVM_INSTRUCTION - Instruction node
- LLVM_TYPE - Type specification
- LLVM_VALUE - Value (constant, register, global)

Features:
- Module structure parsing
- Function declarations and definitions
- Basic block parsing
- Instruction parsing (arithmetic, memory, control flow)
- Type parsing (primitives, pointers, aggregates)
- SSA register tracking

Dependencies:
- llvmir_lexer.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/llvmir/llvmir_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LLVM IR AST Node Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant LLVM_MODULE as Integer is 400
Constant LLVM_FUNCTION as Integer is 401
Constant LLVM_BASIC_BLOCK as Integer is 402
Constant LLVM_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 403
Constant LLVM_TYPE as Integer is 404
Constant LLVM_VALUE as Integer is 405
Constant LLVM_GLOBAL as Integer is 406

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LLVM IR AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Universal LLVM IR AST node carrying enough slots for every node kind
(module, function, basic block, instruction, type, value, global).
Some slots are unused per kind — operands is empty on a value node,
basic_blocks is empty on an instruction — but the uniform layout
keeps allocation and traversal uniform across kinds. Memory overhead
(80 bytes per node vs ~24 for a minimal node) is acceptable because
LLVM IR ASTs are not the dominant memory consumer in the compiler.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
80-byte record (10 x i64). Offsets: node_type (0), name (8), value (16),
type_info (24), operands (32, List), basic_blocks (40, List),
instructions (48, List), attributes (56, Dict), line (64), column (72).
All pointer fields zero-init in create_llvm_node so consumers can
null-check before traversal.
@End Implementation

Type called "LLVMNode":
    node_type as Integer        Note: LLVM_* constant
    name as Integer             Note: Name (function, register, label)
    value as Integer            Note: Value string
    type_info as Integer        Note: Type information
    operands as Integer         Note: List of operands
    basic_blocks as Integer     Note: List of basic blocks (for functions)
    instructions as Integer     Note: List of instructions (for basic blocks)
    attributes as Integer       Note: Dictionary of attributes
    line as Integer             Note: Line number
    column as Integer           Note: Column number
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parser state: holds the lexer, one-token lookahead (current_token),
and sticky-error channel. Single-token lookahead is sufficient for
LLVM IR's grammar — no parser construct needs more than one token
of context to disambiguate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
32-byte struct (4 x i64): lexer pointer at offset 0, current token
at offset 8, owned error message at offset 16, has_error sticky flag
at offset 24. The current_token is pre-fetched in create_llvm_parser
so the parser is ready to use immediately after construction.
@End Implementation

Type called "LLVMParser":
    lexer as Integer            Note: LLVM IR lexer
    current_token as Integer    Note: Current token
    error_message as Integer    Note: Error message (if any)
    has_error as Integer        Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Builds a parser bound to the provided lexer and pre-fetches the first
token so the parser is immediately ready for parse_module or similar
top-level entry. Pre-fetching keeps the rest of the parser's call
sites simple — they only need to call peek_token_type/lexeme without
worrying about the empty-state case.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 32 bytes, OOM short-circuit to 0. Stores lexer pointer at
offset 0, zero-initialises current_token (8), error_message (16),
has_error (24). Calls next_token on the lexer for the first token
and stores it at offset 8, overwriting the zero. Lexer is aliased,
not copied — the parser does not own it.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_llvm_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create LLVM IR parser

    Let parser_size be 32  Note: LLVMParser: 4 fields × 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0   Note: current_token = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: error_message = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0  Note: has_error = false

    Let first_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, first_token

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases parser-owned resources without touching the lexer (which is
owned by the caller). The only owned heap is the error_message buffer
populated by set_parse_error.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null parser returns success (defensive double-free safety). Reads
error_message at offset 16 and frees it via Layout deallocate if
non-null. Then deallocates the 32-byte parser struct. Current_token
is not freed here — tokens are owned by the lexer's token pool.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_llvm_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy LLVM IR parser

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Drives the lexer forward and updates the parser's current-token slot
in one call. The returned token is the new one (now-current), which
some callers use to inspect immediately without a subsequent peek.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads lexer at offset 0, calls next_token, stores the result at
offset 8 (overwriting old current_token), returns the new token.
No null-check on the lexer because the parser is invalid if
construction did not assign it.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, token

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-token lookahead utility — exposes the type tag of the current
token without advancing. Returns TOKEN_EOF for missing/null tokens
so all parser callers can handle "ran past the end" through the same
control flow that handles legitimate EOF.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_token at offset 8 of the parser; if null returns
TOKEN_EOF from the Lexer module. Otherwise reads the token_type
field at offset 0 of the token record.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current token type

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF from Lexer
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Companion to peek_token_type that returns the textual lexeme of the
current token. Used when the parser needs to match on keyword strings
(e.g., distinguishing "ret" from "br" inside the parse_instruction
opcode dispatch) rather than just on token type tags.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_token at offset 8; null returns 0. Otherwise reads the
lexeme pointer at token offset 8. The returned pointer aliases the
lexer's buffer — callers must not free it.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_token_lexeme" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token lexeme

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8

    Return lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean predicate for token type matching. Frequently used inside
parser loops to test the next token without consuming it — for
example, "is the next token a closing paren?" determines whether
the parameter list loop should exit.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls peek_token_type and compares against expected_type. Returns
1 on match, 0 otherwise. Does not advance the parser.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_token_type" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches type

    Let actual_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If actual_type is equal to expected_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes a token of the expected type or fails with the provided
error message. Combines the check-and-advance into one call so
recursive-descent parsing routines stay concise.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls peek_token_type. On mismatch invokes set_parse_error with the
caller's error_msg and returns 0 (caller convention is to bail out).
On match calls advance_token to consume and returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "expect_token" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer, error_msg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect specific token type

    Let actual_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If actual_type is not equal to expected_type:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Records the parse error message. Unlike first-error-wins implementations
elsewhere in this codebase, this one overwrites previous errors —
useful here because deep instruction-level errors usually surface
near the leaf and are more actionable than the outer module-level
report.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads existing error pointer at offset 16; frees if non-null to
prevent leak when overwriting. Allocates msg_length+1 bytes, copies
the message via memory_copy and NUL-terminates. Stores the new
pointer at offset 16. Sets has_error to 1 at offset 24 (sticky).
@End Implementation

Process called "set_parse_error" takes parser as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set parser error message

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    Let msg_length be proc string_length from StringCore with message
    Let new_error be proc allocate from Layout with msg_length plus 1

    If new_error is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_copy from Layout with new_error, message, msg_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with new_error, msg_length, 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, new_error
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 1  Note: has_error = true

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean accessor for the sticky-error flag. The parse_module loop
checks this after each top-level construct to know when to abort.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the integer at offset 24. Flag is 0/1 so the caller can
treat the return as a boolean.
@End Implementation

Process called "has_parse_error" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if parser has error

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24

    Return has_error
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public accessor exposing the (parser-owned) error message pointer
to callers wanting to format diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the int64 at offset 16. Caller must not free — the parser
destructor owns the buffer lifetime.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_error_message" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get error message

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    Return error_message
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Factory for the uniform LLVMNode struct used across all LLVM AST
node kinds. The node_type tag selects which slots are meaningful;
unused slots stay zero and are ignored by downstream code.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 80 bytes, OOM short-circuit to 0. Writes node_type at
offset 0 and zero-initialises all nine other fields explicitly so
no garbage data leaks into child traversal. The List/Dict slots
(operands, basic_blocks, instructions, attributes) lazy-create on
first use via the add_* helpers below.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_llvm_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create LLVM AST node

    Let node_size be 80  Note: LLVMNode: 10 fields × 8 bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0   Note: name = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0  Note: value = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0  Note: type_info = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0  Note: operands = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0  Note: basic_blocks = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0  Note: instructions = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, 0  Note: attributes = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, 0  Note: line = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, 0  Note: column = 0

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Sets the name field on a node by making an owned copy of the source
string. Copying (not aliasing) is necessary because token lexemes
get overwritten by subsequent token reads from the lexer's buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes name_length via string_length. Allocates name_length+1
bytes. If allocation fails returns 0 without modifying the node.
On success copies the bytes via memory_copy, NUL-terminates at the
end byte, and stores the new pointer at node offset 8. Previous
name pointer (if any) is not freed here — caller must ensure no
prior name exists, or accept the leak.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_node_name" takes node as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node name

    Let name_length be proc string_length from StringCore with name
    Let name_copy be proc allocate from Layout with name_length plus 1

    If name_copy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_copy from Layout with name_copy, name, name_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with name_copy, name_length, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, name_copy

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Sets the value field by making an owned copy. Same rationale as
set_node_name: token lexemes are transient so the node must capture
its own copy.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Length+1 byte allocation, memory_copy, NUL-terminate, store pointer
at node offset 16. Returns 0 on OOM, 1 on success. Like set_node_name,
does not free a previously-set value — caller responsibility.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_node_value" takes node as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node value

    Let value_length be proc string_length from StringCore with value
    Let value_copy be proc allocate from Layout with value_length plus 1

    If value_copy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_copy from Layout with value_copy, value, value_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value_copy, value_length, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, value_copy

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lazy-initialises the operands list and appends. Lazy creation avoids
allocating empty List structures for value nodes that never have
operands, which makes up a large fraction of all nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads operands at offset 32. If null, creates a fresh List via
proc create from List and writes it back to offset 32. Then calls
add from List with the operand pointer. Returns 1 on success, 0 on
OOM during List creation.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_operand" takes node as Integer, operand as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add operand to node

    Let operands be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32

    If operands is equal to 0:
        Let new_operands be proc create from List

        If new_operands is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, new_operands
        Set operands to new_operands
    End If

    proc add from List with operands, operand

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lazy-initialises the basic_blocks list and appends. Used to attach a
basic block to its containing function. Same lazy pattern as
add_operand to avoid empty List structures on non-function nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads basic_blocks at offset 40, lazy-creates the List if null,
appends the bb pointer via add from List. Returns 1 on success,
0 on OOM during List creation.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_basic_block" takes node as Integer, bb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add basic block to function

    Let basic_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 40

    If basic_blocks is equal to 0:
        Let new_bbs be proc create from List

        If new_bbs is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, new_bbs
        Set basic_blocks to new_bbs
    End If

    proc add from List with basic_blocks, bb

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lazy-initialises the instructions list and appends. Used to attach
parsed instructions to their containing basic block in source order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads instructions at offset 48, lazy-creates the List if null,
appends the inst pointer. Returns 1 on success, 0 on OOM during
List creation. Order of additions is preserved — important because
LLVM IR is sequential SSA where instruction order determines
dominance and use-def relationships.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_instruction" takes node as Integer, inst as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add instruction to basic block

    Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 48

    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Let new_insts be proc create from List

        If new_insts is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, new_insts
        Set instructions to new_insts
    End If

    proc add from List with instructions, inst

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Type Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses the LLVM IR type grammar and produces a single LLVM_TYPE node
whose name holds the canonical textual spelling of the whole type, so
the type round-trips byte-faithfully through the string-literal HIR
model. The grammar covers: scalar primitives (i1/i8/.../float/double/
ptr, lexer-classified TOKEN_TYPE or the "void"/"ptr" keywords),
pointer suffixes (one or more trailing '*'), fixed-size arrays
([N x ElemType]), vectors (<N x ElemType>), and literal struct types
({T1, T2, ...}). Aggregate element types recurse through parse_type so
nested composites (e.g. [4 x i32]*, {i8*, [2 x i64]}) spell correctly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dispatches on the leading token to parse a base spelling:
  - TOKEN_TYPE: the lexeme is the base spelling.
  - TOKEN_KEYWORD "void"/"ptr": the keyword is the base spelling.
  - TOKEN_LBRACKET: '[' Number 'x' ElemType ']' -> "[N x <elem>]".
  - TOKEN_LANGLE:   '<' Number 'x' ElemType '>' -> "<N x <elem>>".
  - TOKEN_LBRACE:   '{' Type (',' Type)* '}'     -> "{T1, T2}".
After the base, consumes zero or more TOKEN_STAR suffixes, appending a
'*' to the spelling for each (via StringUtils.string_concat). On any
malformed form sets "Expected type" and returns 0. On success creates
an LLVM_TYPE node, stores the assembled spelling as its name, and
returns it.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LLVM IR type and capture its canonical spelling

    Let spelling be proc parse_type_spelling with parser

    If spelling is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected type"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Consume trailing pointer-star suffixes
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_star be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_STAR from Lexer

        If is_star is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser
        Set spelling to proc string_concat from StringUtils with spelling, "*"
    End While

    Let type_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_TYPE
    proc set_node_name with type_node, spelling
    Return type_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a single base type form (no trailing pointer suffix) and returns
its canonical spelling string, or 0 on a malformed form. Split out from
parse_type so the pointer-suffix loop and the aggregate element parses
share one base-form routine. Returns a heap-owned NUL-terminated string
in every success path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switches on the leading token. TOKEN_TYPE / "void" / "ptr" return the
lexeme spelling directly (advancing past it). TOKEN_LBRACKET parses
'[' Number 'x' ElemType ']' assembling "[" + N + " x " + elem + "]".
TOKEN_LANGLE parses the analogous vector form with angle brackets.
TOKEN_LBRACE parses a comma-separated element list into "{" + ... + "}".
Element types recurse through parse_type (capturing their own pointer
suffixes). Any structural mismatch returns 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_type_spelling" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse one base type form, returning its spelling string

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE from Lexer:
        Let lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        Note: Copy so the returned spelling owns its bytes independently
        Let base be proc string_concat from StringUtils with lexeme, ""
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return base
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_KEYWORD from Lexer:
        Let kw be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        Let is_void be proc string_equals from StringCore with kw, "void"
        Let is_ptr be proc string_equals from StringCore with kw, "ptr"

        If is_void is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with "void", ""
        End If

        If is_ptr is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with "ptr", ""
        End If

        Return 0
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LBRACKET from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_sized_aggregate_spelling with parser, 0
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LANGLE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_sized_aggregate_spelling with parser, 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_struct_spelling with parser
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses the two sized-aggregate forms that share the "[N x T]" / "<N x T>"
shape: arrays (square brackets) and vectors (angle brackets). A single
routine parameterised by is_vector handles both, assembling the spelling
"<open>N x <elem><close>" so the round-trip reproduces canonical LLVM IR.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Picks the bracket pair from is_vector (0 -> "[]", 1 -> "<>"). Consumes
the opening bracket. Expects a TOKEN_NUMBER count; captures its lexeme.
Expects the 'x' separator (TOKEN_X, or a TOKEN_KEYWORD "x" since the
lone letter lexes as an identifier). Recurses into parse_type for the
element type (so element pointer suffixes and nested aggregates spell
correctly), then reads the element node's name spelling. Consumes the
closing bracket. Assembles "<open>" + count + " x " + elem + "<close>".
Returns 0 on any structural mismatch.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_sized_aggregate_spelling" takes parser as Integer, is_vector as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse [N x T] (array) or <N x T> (vector) into a spelling

    Let open_bracket be "["
    Let close_bracket be "]"

    If is_vector is equal to 1:
        Set open_bracket to "<"
        Set close_bracket to ">"
    End If

    Note: Consume opening bracket
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Element count
    Let is_number be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer

    If is_number is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count_lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    Let count_copy be proc string_concat from StringUtils with count_lexeme, ""
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: 'x' separator. The single letter 'x' lexes as a TOKEN_KEYWORD
    Note: (identifier) because is_alpha catches it before the single-char
    Note: TOKEN_X branch, so accept either the dedicated TOKEN_X tag or a
    Note: bare "x" keyword lexeme.
    Let sep_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    Let sep_ok be 0

    If sep_type is equal to TOKEN_X from Lexer:
        Set sep_ok to 1
    End If

    If sep_type is equal to TOKEN_KEYWORD from Lexer:
        Let sep_lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        Let is_x_kw be proc string_equals from StringCore with sep_lexeme, "x"

        If is_x_kw is equal to 1:
            Set sep_ok to 1
        End If
    End If

    If sep_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Element type (recurse for nested composites / pointer suffix)
    Let elem_node be proc parse_type with parser

    If elem_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let elem_spelling be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with elem_node, 8

    Note: Closing bracket
    Let is_close be 0

    If is_vector is equal to 1:
        Set is_close to proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RANGLE from Lexer
    Otherwise:
        Set is_close to proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RBRACKET from Lexer
    End If

    If is_close is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Assemble "<open>N x <elem><close>"
    Let part1 be proc string_concat from StringUtils with open_bracket, count_copy
    Let part2 be proc string_concat from StringUtils with part1, " x "
    Let part3 be proc string_concat from StringUtils with part2, elem_spelling
    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with part3, close_bracket

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a literal struct type "{T1, T2, ...}" into its canonical spelling.
Struct fields are arbitrary types, so each field recurses through
parse_type; the fields are joined with ", " between the braces to match
LLVM's canonical printer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes '{'. Loops reading field types via parse_type until '}' or EOF;
between fields emits ", " into the spelling. Reads each field node's name
spelling and concatenates. After the loop consumes '}' and wraps the
joined fields in braces: "{" + fields + "}". The empty struct "{}" is
handled naturally (no fields appended). Returns 0 on EOF before '}'.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_struct_spelling" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse {T1, T2, ...} into a spelling

    Note: Consume '{'
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let fields be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "", ""
    Let first_field be 1

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_rbrace be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer

        If is_rbrace is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        Let tok be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If tok is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Field separator
        If first_field is equal to 0:
            Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

            If is_comma is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If

            Set fields to proc string_concat from StringUtils with fields, ", "
        Otherwise:
            Set first_field to 0
        End If

        Let field_node be proc parse_type with parser

        If field_node is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let field_spelling be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with field_node, 8
        Set fields to proc string_concat from StringUtils with fields, field_spelling
    End While

    Note: Consume '}'
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let opened be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "{", fields
    Let closed be proc string_concat from StringUtils with opened, "}"

    Return closed
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Value Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
LLVM IR values are everything that can appear in an operand slot:
local registers (%0, %var), global identifiers (@func, @global),
numeric constants, string constants, and the three keyword constants
null/true/false. The node kind reflects whether the value is local
(LLVM_VALUE) or global (LLVM_GLOBAL) so downstream passes can
distinguish without re-parsing the leading sigil.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switches on peek token type. TOKEN_LOCAL_ID creates an LLVM_VALUE
node with name. TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID creates an LLVM_GLOBAL node with
name. TOKEN_NUMBER creates an LLVM_VALUE with value (number string).
TOKEN_STRING creates an LLVM_VALUE with value (string lexeme).
TOKEN_KEYWORD dispatches to "null", "true", "false" creating
LLVM_VALUE nodes with the literal as value. Anything else fires
"Expected value" via set_parse_error and returns 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_value" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LLVM IR value (register, global, constant)

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LOCAL_ID from Lexer:
        Let value_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_VALUE
        Let value_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with value_node, value_name
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return value_node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID from Lexer:
        Set value_node to proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_GLOBAL
        Set value_name to proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with value_node, value_name
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return value_node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
        Set value_node to proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_VALUE
        Let value_str be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_value with value_node, value_str
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return value_node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        Set value_node to proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_VALUE
        Set value_str to proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_value with value_node, value_str
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return value_node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_KEYWORD from Lexer:
        Let lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        Let is_null be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "null"
        Let is_true be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "true"
        Let is_false be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "false"

        If is_null is equal to 1:
            Set value_node to proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_VALUE
            proc set_node_value with value_node, "null"
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return value_node
        End If

        If is_true is equal to 1:
            Set value_node to proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_VALUE
            proc set_node_value with value_node, "true"
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return value_node
        End If

        If is_false is equal to 1:
            Set value_node to proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_VALUE
            proc set_node_value with value_node, "false"
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return value_node
        End If
    End If

    proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected value"
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Instruction Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The instruction parser is the most complex parser routine. LLVM IR
instructions have heterogeneous shapes: ret/br/call/load/store/alloca
each take different operand patterns; arithmetic instructions follow
a uniform "type op1, op2" pattern. Specialised handling for the
control-flow and memory opcodes produces semantically-correct ASTs;
the arithmetic fallback covers the regular pattern shared by add,
sub, mul, sdiv, udiv, icmp, etc.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an LLVM_INSTRUCTION node up-front. If current token is
TOKEN_LOCAL_ID, captures it as the result-assignment register name
and expects `=`. Then expects TOKEN_KEYWORD for the opcode, stores
opcode as the node's value, and advances. Six specialised opcode
branches follow: ret (parses type then optional value, void-typed
ret has no value), br (parses either unconditional `br label %X` or
conditional `br i1 %cond, label %T, label %F`), alloca (parses single
type), load (type, comma, ptr-type, ptr-value), store (type, value,
comma, ptr-type, ptr-value), call (ret-type, callee, paren-arg list).
Anything else falls through to the binary-arithmetic pattern:
type, op1, comma, op2.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_instruction" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LLVM IR instruction

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    Let inst_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_INSTRUCTION

    If inst_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check for result assignment (%result = ...)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LOCAL_ID from Lexer:
        Let result_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with inst_node, result_name
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Expect equals
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUALS from Lexer, "Expected '=' after register"
    End If

    Note: Parse instruction opcode
    Let is_keyword be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_KEYWORD from Lexer

    If is_keyword is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected instruction keyword"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_value with inst_node, opcode
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Parse operands based on instruction type
    Let is_ret be proc string_equals from StringCore with opcode, "ret"
    Let is_br be proc string_equals from StringCore with opcode, "br"
    Let is_call be proc string_equals from StringCore with opcode, "call"
    Let is_load be proc string_equals from StringCore with opcode, "load"
    Let is_store be proc string_equals from StringCore with opcode, "store"
    Let is_alloca be proc string_equals from StringCore with opcode, "alloca"

    If is_ret is equal to 1:
        Note: ret type value OR ret void
        Let type_node be proc parse_type with parser

        If type_node is not equal to 0:
            proc add_operand with inst_node, type_node

            Note: Check if void or has value
            Let type_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 8
            Let is_void be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_name, "void"

            If is_void is equal to 0:
                Let value_node be proc parse_value with parser

                If value_node is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_operand with inst_node, value_node
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Return inst_node
    End If

    If is_br is equal to 1:
        Note: br label OR br i1 cond, label true, label false
        Let is_label be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_KEYWORD from Lexer

        If is_label is equal to 1:
            Let lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
            Let is_label_kw be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "label"

            If is_label_kw is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let target be proc parse_value with parser
                proc add_operand with inst_node, target
                Return inst_node
            End If
        End If

        Note: Conditional branch
        Let cond_type be proc parse_type with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, cond_type

        Let cond_value be proc parse_value with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, cond_value

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer, "Expected ','"

        Note: Parse true label
        Set lexeme to proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        Set is_label_kw to proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "label"

        If is_label_kw is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Let true_label be proc parse_value with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, true_label

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer, "Expected ','"

        Note: Parse false label
        Set lexeme to proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        Set is_label_kw to proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "label"

        If is_label_kw is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Let false_label be proc parse_value with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, false_label

        Return inst_node
    End If

    If is_alloca is equal to 1:
        Note: alloca type
        Set type_node to proc parse_type with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, type_node
        Return inst_node
    End If

    If is_load is equal to 1:
        Note: load type, ptr value
        Set type_node to proc parse_type with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, type_node

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer, "Expected ','"

        Let ptr_type be proc parse_type with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, ptr_type

        Let ptr_value be proc parse_value with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, ptr_value

        Return inst_node
    End If

    If is_store is equal to 1:
        Note: store type value, ptr destination
        Set type_node to proc parse_type with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, type_node

        Set value_node to proc parse_value with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, value_node

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer, "Expected ','"

        Set ptr_type to proc parse_type with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, ptr_type

        Set ptr_value to proc parse_value with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, ptr_value

        Return inst_node
    End If

    If is_call is equal to 1:
        Note: call return_type function_name(args)
        Let ret_type be proc parse_type with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, ret_type

        Let func_name be proc parse_value with parser
        proc add_operand with inst_node, func_name

        Note: Parse argument list
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer, "Expected '('"

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let is_rparen be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

            If is_rparen is equal to 1:
                Break
            End If

            Let arg_type be proc parse_type with parser
            proc add_operand with inst_node, arg_type

            Let arg_value be proc parse_value with parser
            proc add_operand with inst_node, arg_value

            Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

            If is_comma is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')'"

        Return inst_node
    End If

    Note: Binary operations (add, sub, mul, etc.)
    Note: Parse: type operand1, operand2
    Set type_node to proc parse_type with parser

    If type_node is not equal to 0:
        proc add_operand with inst_node, type_node

        Let op1 be proc parse_value with parser

        If op1 is not equal to 0:
            proc add_operand with inst_node, op1

            Set is_comma to proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

            If is_comma is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser

                Let op2 be proc parse_value with parser

                If op2 is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_operand with inst_node, op2
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return inst_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Basic Block Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Distinguishing a basic-block label from an instruction requires a
single-token lookahead: a label is `<identifier>:` whereas a result
register is `<local-id> =` and an opcode keyword is `<keyword> <operand>`.
This helper performs the lookahead non-destructively so both the label
parse and the next-block-boundary detection can ask "is the token after
the current one a colon?" without permanently advancing the parser.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Saves the full lexer cursor (position @16, line @24, column @32) and the
parser's current_token pointer @8. Advances one token, reads the new
token's type, then restores the lexer cursor exactly and re-fetches the
token via next_token so the parser's current_token is identical to its
pre-call state (lexemes are owned copies, so re-fetch reproduces the
same logical token). Returns 1 if the looked-ahead token is TOKEN_COLON,
0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "lookahead_is_colon" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Non-destructive one-token lookahead for a ':' terminator

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let saved_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let saved_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let saved_line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let saved_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc advance_token with parser
    Let next_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    Note: Restore the lexer cursor and re-fetch the original current token
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, saved_pos
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, saved_line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, saved_column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, saved_token

    If next_type is equal to TOKEN_COLON from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Basic blocks in LLVM IR are sequences of instructions starting with
an optional label and ending with a terminator (br/ret/switch/etc).
The parser treats end-of-block as "next token is another label"
(an identifier followed by colon), end of function `}`, or EOF. Reading
instructions until that boundary produces the right block structure even
without parsing terminator types specifically.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an LLVM_BASIC_BLOCK node. Parses an OPTIONAL label: a leading
TOKEN_LOCAL_ID / TOKEN_NUMBER / TOKEN_KEYWORD / TOKEN_LABEL is treated
as a label only when lookahead_is_colon confirms a ':' follows; the
label name is captured and the ':' consumed. When no ':' follows, the
block is unlabeled (implicit entry) and parsing proceeds straight to the
instruction loop. The loop reads instructions until TOKEN_EOF,
TOKEN_RBRACE (end of function), or the next-block boundary (an
identifier token followed by ':' per lookahead_is_colon). Non-instruction
or null instruction returns also break out. Each successful instruction
appends to the block via add_instruction.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_basic_block" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LLVM IR basic block

    Let bb_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_BASIC_BLOCK

    If bb_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse the optional block label. LLVM IR labels are bare
    Note: identifiers (lexed as TOKEN_KEYWORD), numeric labels
    Note: (TOKEN_NUMBER), or %-prefixed locals (TOKEN_LOCAL_ID), in
    Note: every case followed by a ':'. The first block of a function
    Note: frequently has NO explicit label (implicit entry); in that
    Note: case the leading token is an instruction keyword / local-id
    Note: NOT followed by ':', so the label is absent and parsing falls
    Note: straight through to the instruction loop.
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    Let label_is_candidate be 0

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LOCAL_ID from Lexer:
        Set label_is_candidate to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
        Set label_is_candidate to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_KEYWORD from Lexer:
        Set label_is_candidate to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LABEL from Lexer:
        Set label_is_candidate to 1
    End If

    If label_is_candidate is equal to 1:
        Note: Confirm the candidate is a label by looking ahead for ':'.
        Let label_followed_by_colon be proc lookahead_is_colon with parser

        If label_followed_by_colon is equal to 1:
            Let label_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
            proc set_node_name with bb_node, label_name
            proc advance_token with parser

            Note: Consume the ':' terminator
            proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer, "Expected ':' after label"
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse instructions until next label or end of function
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type2 be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type2 is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type2 is equal to TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Detect the start of the next basic block: an identifier
        Note: token (local-id / number / bare keyword) immediately
        Note: followed by ':'. Distinguishes a label from a result
        Note: register (which is followed by '=') or an opcode keyword
        Note: (which is followed by an operand, not ':').
        Let boundary_candidate be 0

        If token_type2 is equal to TOKEN_LOCAL_ID from Lexer:
            Set boundary_candidate to 1
        End If

        If token_type2 is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
            Set boundary_candidate to 1
        End If

        If token_type2 is equal to TOKEN_KEYWORD from Lexer:
            Set boundary_candidate to 1
        End If

        If token_type2 is equal to TOKEN_LABEL from Lexer:
            Set boundary_candidate to 1
        End If

        If boundary_candidate is equal to 1:
            Let next_is_colon be proc lookahead_is_colon with parser

            If next_is_colon is equal to 1:
                Break  Note: Start of next basic block
            End If
        End If

        Let inst be proc parse_instruction with parser

        If inst is not equal to 0:
            proc add_instruction with bb_node, inst
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return bb_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Function Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses an LLVM function definition starting with `define`. The full
form is `define RetType @name(ParamType %param, ...) { body }`.
Return type goes into the type_info slot; basic blocks of the body
go into the basic_blocks list. Parameters are attached as operand
nodes via add_operand so they can be enumerated by traversal passes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an LLVM_FUNCTION node. Verifies the current token is the
keyword "define" via string_equals on the lexeme; mismatch sets
"Expected 'define'" and returns 0. Advances, parses return type into
type_info (node offset 24). Expects TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID for the function
name, captures it via set_node_name, advances. Expects `(`. The
parameter loop reads param_type, then optional param_name
(peek_token_lexeme), constructs an LLVM_VALUE node, stores the type
in its type_info slot and sets the name when a local id is present.
First-iteration flag suppresses the comma check; subsequent
iterations expect `,` first. After parameters are gathered into
param_list, iterates and add_operand's each onto func_node. Expects
`)` and `{`. Then loops reading basic_blocks until `}` or EOF.
Finally expects `}` as the function terminator.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_function" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LLVM IR function definition

    Let func_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_FUNCTION

    If func_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Expect 'define' keyword
    Let lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    Let is_define be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "define"

    If is_define is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected 'define'"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Parse return type
    Let ret_type be proc parse_type with parser

    If ret_type is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with func_node, 24, ret_type
    End If

    Note: Parse function name (@name)
    Let is_global be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID from Lexer

    If is_global is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected function name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let func_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_name with func_node, func_name
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Parse parameter list
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer, "Expected '('"

    Note: Parse function parameters: type %name, type %name, ...
    Let param_list be proc create from List
    Let first_param be 1
    Let param_lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_rparen be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

        If is_rparen is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Forward-progress / malformed-input guard: stop at EOF or
        Note: at a closing brace so a missing ')' cannot spin the loop.
        Let ptok_top be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If ptok_top is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If ptok_top is equal to TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Capture the lexer cursor to detect zero-consumption loops.
        Let param_pos_before be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_lexer, 16

        Note: Parse comma separator after first parameter
        If first_param is equal to 0:
            proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer, "Expected ','"
        Otherwise:
            Set first_param to 0
        End If

        Note: Parse parameter type
        Let param_type be proc parse_type with parser

        Note: Build the parameter as an LLVM_VALUE node carrying the
        Note: type in its type_info slot and the register name (if any).
        Let param_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_VALUE

        If param_type is not equal to 0:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with param_node, 24, param_type
        End If

        Note: Parameter name (starts with %) is optional in declarations
        Let param_tok_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If param_tok_type is equal to TOKEN_LOCAL_ID from Lexer:
            Let param_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
            proc set_node_name with param_node, param_name
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        proc add from List with param_list, param_node

        Note: If the iteration consumed no input (malformed parameter),
        Note: abandon the loop to guarantee termination.
        Let param_pos_after be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_lexer, 16

        If param_pos_after is equal to param_pos_before:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Attach parameter list to function node operands in order
    Let i be 0
    Let param_count be proc size from List with param_list
    While i is less than param_count:
        Let param be proc get from List with param_list, i
        proc add_operand with func_node, param
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')'"

    Note: Parse function body
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer, "Expected '{'"

    Note: Parse basic blocks
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_rbrace be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer

        If is_rbrace is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Forward-progress guard: capture the lexer cursor before
        Note: the block parse so a block that consumes nothing cannot
        Note: spin the loop forever.
        Let body_lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
        Let pos_before be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with body_lexer, 16

        Let bb be proc parse_basic_block with parser

        If bb is not equal to 0:
            proc add_basic_block with func_node, bb
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If

        Let pos_after be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with body_lexer, 16

        If pos_after is equal to pos_before:
            Note: No tokens consumed — abandon to guarantee termination
            Break
        End If
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer, "Expected '}'"

    Return func_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Module-Level Declaration Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A function declaration (prototype) has the same prefix as a definition
but ends at the parameter list with no body: `declare RetType @name
(ParamType, ...)`. It is represented with the same LLVM_FUNCTION node
kind as a definition; the absence of basic blocks distinguishes a
declaration from a definition for downstream consumers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an LLVM_FUNCTION node. Consumes the "declare" keyword, parses
the return type into the type_info slot, expects a TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID for
the callee name, and parses a parenthesised parameter-type list. Each
parameter is an LLVM_VALUE node carrying only the type (declarations
typically omit parameter names). Parameters are attached via
add_operand. No body braces are consumed.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_function_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LLVM IR function declaration (prototype, no body)

    Let decl_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_FUNCTION

    If decl_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Consume 'declare'
    Let lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    Let is_declare be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "declare"

    If is_declare is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected 'declare'"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Return type into type_info slot
    Let ret_type be proc parse_type with parser

    If ret_type is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with decl_node, 24, ret_type
    End If

    Note: Function name (@name)
    Let is_global be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID from Lexer

    If is_global is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected function name in declaration"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let decl_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_name with decl_node, decl_name
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Parameter-type list
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer, "Expected '('"

    Let first_param be 1

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_rparen be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

        If is_rparen is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        If first_param is equal to 0:
            proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer, "Expected ','"
        Otherwise:
            Set first_param to 0
        End If

        Let param_type be proc parse_type with parser

        If param_type is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let param_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_VALUE
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with param_node, 24, param_type

        Note: Declarations may carry an optional parameter name
        Let ptok be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If ptok is equal to TOKEN_LOCAL_ID from Lexer:
            Let pname be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
            proc set_node_name with param_node, pname
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        proc add_operand with decl_node, param_node
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')'"

    Return decl_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A global variable definition is `@name = [linkage] global|constant
Type Initializer`. The node captures the global's name, whether it is
mutable (global) or immutable (constant) as its value string, the
declared type in type_info, and the initializer expression as an
operand when present.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an LLVM_GLOBAL node. Expects TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID for the name,
captures it, advances. Expects `=`. Skips any optional linkage/visibility
keyword tokens that precede the global/constant keyword by consuming
keyword tokens until the global/constant marker is found (bounded by a
forward-progress break on non-keyword tokens). Records "global" or
"constant" as the node value. Parses the type into type_info. If a
value token follows (not end-of-statement), parses the initializer via
parse_value and attaches it as an operand.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_global_variable" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LLVM IR global variable definition

    Let global_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_GLOBAL

    If global_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Global name (@name)
    Let is_global be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID from Lexer

    If is_global is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected global variable name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let global_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_name with global_node, global_name
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Expect '='
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUALS from Lexer, "Expected '=' in global definition"

    Note: Consume optional linkage/visibility keywords until the
    Note: global/constant marker. Forward progress is guaranteed: each
    Note: iteration either matches the marker (and breaks) or consumes
    Note: one keyword token; a non-keyword token also breaks.
    Let marker_found be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_kw be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_KEYWORD from Lexer

        If is_kw is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let kw_lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        Let is_global_kw be proc string_equals from StringCore with kw_lexeme, "global"
        Let is_constant_kw be proc string_equals from StringCore with kw_lexeme, "constant"

        If is_global_kw is equal to 1:
            proc set_node_value with global_node, "global"
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set marker_found to 1
            Break
        End If

        If is_constant_kw is equal to 1:
            proc set_node_value with global_node, "constant"
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set marker_found to 1
            Break
        End If

        Note: Optional linkage/visibility/thread-local keyword — skip
        proc advance_token with parser
    End While

    Note: Declared type into type_info slot
    Let var_type be proc parse_type with parser

    If var_type is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with global_node, 24, var_type
    End If

    Note: Optional initializer value
    Let next_type be proc peek_token_type with parser
    Let has_init be 0

    If next_type is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
        Set has_init to 1
    End If

    If next_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        Set has_init to 1
    End If

    If next_type is equal to TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID from Lexer:
        Set has_init to 1
    End If

    If next_type is equal to TOKEN_LOCAL_ID from Lexer:
        Set has_init to 1
    End If

    If next_type is equal to TOKEN_KEYWORD from Lexer:
        Let init_lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        Let init_is_null be proc string_equals from StringCore with init_lexeme, "null"
        Let init_is_true be proc string_equals from StringCore with init_lexeme, "true"
        Let init_is_false be proc string_equals from StringCore with init_lexeme, "false"

        If init_is_null is equal to 1:
            Set has_init to 1
        End If

        If init_is_true is equal to 1:
            Set has_init to 1
        End If

        If init_is_false is equal to 1:
            Set has_init to 1
        End If
    End If

    If has_init is equal to 1:
        Let init_value be proc parse_value with parser

        If init_value is not equal to 0:
            proc add_operand with global_node, init_value
        End If
    End If

    Return global_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A named type definition is `%name = type Body`. It introduces a type
alias usable elsewhere in the module. The node carries the alias name
and the aliased type in its type_info slot.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an LLVM_TYPE node. Expects TOKEN_LOCAL_ID for the %name alias,
captures it, advances. Expects `=`. Consumes the "type" keyword.
Parses the aliased type into type_info via parse_type for primitive
spellings. Aggregate bodies (struct {..}) begin with `{`; when the
next token is a brace the brace-delimited body is consumed token-by-
token with depth tracking so the alias parse terminates correctly,
and the alias is recorded with value "struct". Forward progress is
guaranteed inside the brace loop by always advancing or breaking on
EOF.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_type_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LLVM IR named type definition (%name = type ...)

    Let type_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_TYPE

    If type_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Alias name (%name)
    Let is_local be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LOCAL_ID from Lexer

    If is_local is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected type name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let alias_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_name with type_node, alias_name
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Expect '='
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUALS from Lexer, "Expected '=' in type definition"

    Note: Consume 'type' keyword
    Let lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    Let is_type_kw be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "type"

    If is_type_kw is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected 'type' keyword"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Aggregate struct body { ... } or a primitive type spelling
    Let body_tok be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If body_tok is equal to TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer:
        proc set_node_value with type_node, "struct"
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Consume the brace-delimited body with depth tracking
        Let depth be 1

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let t be proc peek_token_type with parser

            If t is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Break
            End If

            If t is equal to TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer:
                Set depth to depth plus 1
            End If

            If t is equal to TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer:
                Set depth to depth minus 1

                If depth is equal to 0:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                    Break
                End If
            End If

            proc advance_token with parser
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Let aliased_type be proc parse_type with parser

        If aliased_type is not equal to 0:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with type_node, 24, aliased_type
        End If
    End If

    Return type_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A target directive is `target triple = "..."` or `target datalayout
= "..."`. The node captures which kind (triple or datalayout) as its
name and the quoted spec string as its value. These directives drive
backend code generation so they must survive translation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an LLVM_VALUE node tagged via name with the directive kind.
Consumes the "target" keyword. Reads the next keyword (triple or
datalayout) as the directive kind name. Expects `=`. Captures the
following TOKEN_STRING lexeme as the directive value via set_node_value.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_target_info" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LLVM IR target directive (triple/datalayout)

    Let target_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_VALUE

    If target_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Consume 'target'
    Let lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    Let is_target be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "target"

    If is_target is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected 'target'"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Directive kind (triple or datalayout) as the node name
    Let kind_tok be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_KEYWORD from Lexer

    If kind_tok is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected target directive kind"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let kind_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_name with target_node, kind_name
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Expect '='
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUALS from Lexer, "Expected '=' in target directive"

    Note: Spec string value
    Let is_str be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_STRING from Lexer

    If is_str is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected target spec string"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let spec be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_value with target_node, spec
    proc advance_token with parser

    Return target_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
An attribute group definition is `attributes #N = { attr attr ... }`.
The node records the group identifier and the brace-delimited attribute
list. Attribute groups are referenced by functions; preserving them
keeps the module structurally complete.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an LLVM_VALUE node. Consumes the "attributes" keyword. The
group id token (#N) is lexed as TOKEN_METADATA-like or generic; the
parser captures whatever lexeme follows as the node name and advances.
Expects `=`. Consumes the brace-delimited body with depth tracking so
nested braces terminate correctly; forward progress is guaranteed by
advancing every iteration or breaking on EOF.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_attributes" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LLVM IR attribute group definition

    Let attr_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_VALUE

    If attr_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Consume 'attributes'
    Let lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    Let is_attributes be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "attributes"

    If is_attributes is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected 'attributes'"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Group identifier (whatever token form the lexer produced)
    Let id_tok be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If id_tok is not equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
        Let id_lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_name with attr_node, id_lexeme
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Expect '='
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUALS from Lexer, "Expected '=' in attributes group"

    Note: Brace-delimited attribute body with depth tracking
    Let open_brace be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer

    If open_brace is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let depth be 1

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let t be proc peek_token_type with parser

            If t is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Break
            End If

            If t is equal to TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer:
                Set depth to depth plus 1
            End If

            If t is equal to TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer:
                Set depth to depth minus 1

                If depth is equal to 0:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                    Break
                End If
            End If

            proc advance_token with parser
        End While
    End If

    Return attr_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Module Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level entry point for parsing a complete LLVM IR module. A module
mixes function definitions (define), declarations (declare), global
variables (@name = ...), named type definitions (%name = type ...),
target triple/datalayout directives, and attributes groups. Dispatch
is driven by the current token's type for sigil-led forms (@name,
%name) and by the keyword lexeme for word-led forms.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an LLVM_MODULE node. Loops over module contents until
TOKEN_EOF. Each iteration peeks the token type and lexeme and
dispatches:
  - lexeme "define" -> parse_function, attached via add_basic_block
    (the function goes into the basic_blocks slot of the module —
    this is a reuse of the slot since the module itself has no real
    BBs).
  - lexeme "declare" -> parse_function_declaration for prototype-only
    declarations (attached via add_operand).
  - TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID -> parse_global_variable for @name module-scoped
    variables (attached via add_operand).
  - TOKEN_LOCAL_ID -> parse_type_definition for %name named type
    aliases (attached via add_operand).
  - lexeme "target" -> parse_target_info (triple/datalayout).
  - lexeme "attributes" -> parse_attributes for attribute group
    definitions.
  - Anything else: skip one token to avoid infinite loop on
    unrecognised syntax (forward-progress guarantee).
After each iteration checks has_parse_error; non-zero returns 0 to
abandon the module on first failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_module" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse LLVM IR module (top-level entry point)

    Let module_node be proc create_llvm_node with LLVM_MODULE

    If module_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse module contents
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Let lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser

        Note: Check for function definition
        Let is_define be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "define"

        If is_define is equal to 1:
            Let func be proc parse_function with parser

            If func is not equal to 0:
                proc add_basic_block with module_node, func
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: Handle other module-level declarations. The global
            Note: and named-type forms are recognised by token TYPE
            Note: (TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID for @name, TOKEN_LOCAL_ID for %name),
            Note: while declare/target/attributes are bare keyword
            Note: lexemes classified as TOKEN_KEYWORD.
            Let is_declare be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "declare"
            Let is_target be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "target"
            Let is_attributes be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "attributes"
            Let is_global_id be 0
            Let is_local_id be 0

            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID from Lexer:
                Set is_global_id to 1
            End If

            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LOCAL_ID from Lexer:
                Set is_local_id to 1
            End If

            If is_declare is equal to 1:
                Note: Function declaration (prototype)
                Let decl be proc parse_function_declaration with parser
                If decl is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_operand with module_node, decl
                End If
            Otherwise If is_global_id is equal to 1:
                Note: Global variable declaration (@name = ...)
                Let global be proc parse_global_variable with parser
                If global is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_operand with module_node, global
                End If
            Otherwise If is_local_id is equal to 1:
                Note: Named type definition (%name = type ...)
                Let type_def be proc parse_type_definition with parser
                If type_def is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_operand with module_node, type_def
                End If
            Otherwise If is_target is equal to 1:
                Note: Target triple or datalayout
                Let target_info be proc parse_target_info with parser
                If target_info is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_operand with module_node, target_info
                End If
            Otherwise If is_attributes is equal to 1:
                Note: Function attributes definition
                Let attrs be proc parse_attributes with parser
                If attrs is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_operand with module_node, attrs
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Note: Unknown declaration - skip token to avoid infinite loop
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If
        End If

        Let has_error be proc has_parse_error with parser

        If has_error is equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
    End While

    Return module_node
End Process
